Movie Statistics

Victoria Wingo

28 April 2022

Datasets

Movies

The movies dataset serves as a corrected version of the original dataset Highest_Hollywood_Grossing_Movies taken from kaggle, covering Hollywood films through 2021. Missing data has been added manually and the variable runtime has been converted from the 00h 00m format to minutes.

Average Sales by Runtimes

Fig. 1.1 On average, a longer movie will see more sales than a shorter movie, but sales become less predictable with longer movies.

Average Sales by License

Fig. 2.1 On average, PG-13 movies sees more sales, while PG and G movies see about the same amount of sales.

Average Runtimes by License

Fig. 3.1 On average, PG-13 and R rated movies have about the same runtime.

Movies with the Most World Sales of Their Year

Fig. 5.1 These movies had the most sales of their year, showing a strong showing for superhero movies in the past 10 years.

Fig. 5.2 A table showing the 10 top films of their year.
title release_year distributor world_sales_mil
Avatar (2009) 2009 Twentieth Century Fox 2847.246
Avengers: Endgame (2019) 2019 Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures 2797.501
Titanic (1997) 1997 Paramount Pictures 2201.647
Star Wars: Episode VII - The Force Awakens (2015) 2015 Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures 2069.522
Avengers: Infinity War (2018) 2018 Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures 2048.360
Spider-Man: No Way Home (2021) 2021 Sony Pictures Entertainment (SPE) 1544.456
The Avengers (2012) 2012 Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures 1518.816
Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part 2 (2011) 2011 Warner Bros. 1342.322
Star Wars: Episode VIII - The Last Jedi (2017) 2017 Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures 1332.699
Frozen (2013) 2013 Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures 1281.508

Note that 9 out of 10 of the films in Fig. 5.2 were released after 2009. Not only that, 6 were distributed by Walt Disney Studios. Twentieth Century Fox is now owned by Disney and will release sequels for the top-spot film “Avatar.” While the film ‘Spider-Man: No Way Home’ was distributed by Sony, they used Marvel Studios, also owned by Disney.
